<?xml version="1.0" encoding="UTF-8"?>
<knowledge>
	<title>Pacemaker/ICD/ILR patient advice</title>
	<description> This system helps a secratary to determine the correct treatment for a calling patient. </description>
	<goal name="advice">
        <answer value="Wrong_place">
        The caller is at the wrong place, this is the pacemaker/icd department. 
        If they are still suffering from complaints, connect them to the according department.  
        </answer>      
        <answer value="False_alarm">
        In this case the person who said that their alarm went off might have misheard or misfelt this.
        They either said that they heard a beep while their icd can only vibrate,
        or the other way around.
        </answer>
		<answer value="Appointment_today_1">
        The cause might be a frenic nerve stimulation, 
        could be that the diaphragm gets stimulated because the CRT might be set too high. 
        It can be annoying but it is not live threatening.
        Advice: Make an appointment for today.
        </answer>
        <answer value="Appointment_today_2">
        The cause needs to be investigated, i.e. if the shock was correct or not.
        Advice: Make an appointment for today.
        Note: They are not allowed to drive!
        </answer>
        <answer value="Appointment_today_3">
        The symptoms could be caused by a heart rhythm disorder, 
        it should be investigated whether the loss of conciousness had to do with the heart rhythm disorder.
        Advice: Make an appointment for today
        </answer>
        <answer value="Appointment_today_4">
        Causes could be: 
        - Battery almost empty EOS(end of service)
        - Device made lead measurements that fall outside the boundaries of the settings of the icd.
          This could point to a broken lead, with the risk of a uncorrect shock.
        - Or loss of pacemaker functioning.
        Advice: Make an appointment for today
        </answer>
        <answer value="Appointment_week">
        Might be a malfunction of the pacemaker or a heart rhythm disturbance.
        Advice: Make an appointment for this week.
        </answer>
        <answer value="Appointment_week_2">
        It needs to be investigated whether the recorded problems show a heart rhythm disorder 
        which could explain the problems. 
        Advice: Make an appointment for this week.
        </answer>
        <answer value="Not_directed">
        Based on these questions, the problems that the patient is having do not seem to point
        towards their pacemaker/ICD/ILR. 
        Advice: Let them make an appointment with their doctor/general practioner,
                in order to see what the cause of the problem could be.
        </answer>
        <answer value="Call_112_1">
        With multiple shocks it might be the case the the ICD is disfunctioning, the patient might have 
        an adverse heart condition, or there are too many heart rhythm disturbances, this will not 
        solve itself.
        Advice: Call 112 immediately!
        </answer>
        <answer value="Call_112_2">
        A shock did not resolve the patient's complaints. This means that there is the
        possibility of another shock and something else being wrong.
        Advice: Call 112 immediately!
        </answer>
	</goal>

